c%3Fformat%3Djpeg%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%221334%5C%22%3E%3Cfigcaption%3EThe%20world's%20largest%20aircraft%20carrier%20USS%20Gerald%20R.%20Ford%20(CVN%2078)%20and%20the%20Ticonderoga-class%20guided-missile%20cruiser%20USS%20Normandy%20(CG%2060)%20steam%20in%20formation%20in%20the%20Mediterranean%20Sea%2C%20Aug.%2021%2C%202023.%3Cp%3EMC2%20Jackson%20Adkins%2FUS%20Navy%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Ffigcaption%3E%3C%2Ffigure%3E%3Cul%3E%3Cli%3ENATO's%20naval%20power%20is%20far%20superior%20to%20Russia's%2C%20which%20mainly%20exists%20to%20defend%20its%20motherland.%3C%2Fli%3E%3Cli%3ERussia's%20fear%20is%20that%20NATO%20ships%20could%20launch%20strike%20missiles%20at%20the%20Russian%20heartland.%3C%2Fli%3E%3Cli%3EIt%20could%20force%20Russia%20to%20beef%20up%20maritime%20defenses%20and%20distract%20from%20rebuilding%20its%20battered%20army.%3C%2Fli%3E%3C%2Ful%3E%3Cp%3E%3Cspan%3EThe%20age-old%20rivalry%20between%20continental%20and%20maritime%20nations%20has%20always%20been%20an%20exercise%20in%20frustration.%20For%20example%2C%20Napoleon%20and%20Hitler%20fumed%20at%20the%20English%20Channel%20and%20Royal%20Navy%20that%20kept%20their%20mighty%20armies%20from%20conquering%20Britain.%20Conversely%2C%20the%20British%20needed%20a%20continental%20power%20with%20a%20big%20army%20%E2%80%94%20usually%20Russia%20%E2%80%94%20to%20fight%20the%20French%20and%20Germans%20on%20land.%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%3Cspan%3EToday%2C%20NATO's%20naval%20power%20is%20far%20superior%20to%20Russia's.%20The%20problem%20is%20Russia%20has%20always%20been%20a%20continental%20power%20whose%20strength%20rested%20on%20its%20army.%20NATO%20may%20dominate%20the%20oceans%2C%20but%20that%20may%20not%20be%20much%20help%20if%20Russian%20tanks%20invade%20the%20Baltic%20States%20or%20Poland.%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%3Cspan%3ESo%2C%20how%20can%20NATO%20exploit%20its%20naval%20advantage%3F%20Two%20British%20experts%20have%20an%20idea%3A%20use%20NATO's%20navies%20to%20wage%20psychological%20warfare%20against%20Russia.%20Or%20more%20specifically%2C%20use%20naval%20power%20to%20scare%20Moscow%20into%20allocating%20its%20scarce%20resources%20to%20defending%20its%20huge%20coastlines%20rather%20than%20invading%20neighbors.%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%3Cspan%3E%26quot%3BBy%20forcing%20Russia%20to%20commit%20to%20its%20own%20defenses%20in%20the%20maritime%20domain%2C%20it%20would%20divert%20critical%20Russian%20resources%20to%20tasks%20that%20the%20Alliance%20%5BNATO%5D%20deems%20less%20threatening%2C%26quot%3B%20wrote%20Sidharth%20Kaushal%20and%20Rene%20Balletta%20in%20an%20%3C%2Fspan%3E%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.rusi.org%2Fexplore-our-research%2Fpublications%2Foccasional-papers%2Fasymmetric-approach-use-maritime-forces-competing-russia%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3E%3Cspan%3Eessay%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fa%3E%3Cspan%3E%20for%20Britain's%20Royal%20United%20Services%20Institute%20think%20tank.%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%3Cspan%3EFor%20America%20and%20Britain%2C%20the%20sea%20has%20been%20a%20friend%3A%20a%20buffer%20against%20invasion%2C%20a%20highway%20to%20overseas%20empire%2C%20and%20a%20way%20to%20ensure%20that%20wars%20are%20fought%20on%20foreign%20soil.%20But%20for%20Russia%2C%20with%20nearly%2024%2C000%20miles%20of%20coastline%20across%20Europe%20and%20Asia%2C%20the%20sea%20has%20historically%20been%20a%20source%20of%20vulnerability.%20Though%20the%20Russian%20Navy%20is%20one%20of%20the%20%3C%2Fspan%3E%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wdmmw.org%2Frussian-navy.php%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3E%3Cspan%3Eworld's%20largest%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fa%3E%3Cspan%3E%2C%20it%20mainly%20exists%20to%20protect%20the%20motherland%2C%20to%20support%20the%20army%2C%20and%20to%20provide%20strategic%20firepower%20such%20as%20from%20nuclear%20missile%20subs.%20Many%20of%20the%20cruise%20missiles%20that%20have%20pummeled%20Ukrainian%20cities%20for%20the%20past%20two%20years%20have%20been%20launched%20by%20the%20Black%20Sea%20Fleet.%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%3Cspan%3EBut%20control%20of%20the%20seas%2C%20in%20the%20way%20that%20the%20famous%2019th%20Century%20American%20naval%20theorist%20%3C%2Fspan%3E%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fthediplomat.com%2F2014%2F12%2Fthe-geopolitical-vision-of-alfred-thayer-mahan%2F%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3E%3Cspan%3EAlfred%20Thayer%20Mahan%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fa%3E%3Cspan%3E%20defined%20it%2C%20is%20not%20the%20Russian%20Navy's%20mission.%20%26quot%3BRather%20than%20naval%20combat%20per%20se%2C%20the%20purpose%20of%20Russian%20sea%20power%20is%20to%20ensure%20that%20the%20Russian%20state%20can%20compete%20and%20engage%20in%20conflict%20safely%20and%20effectively%2C%26quot%3B%20the%20essay%20said.%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%3Cspan%3EIn%20the%20Crimean%20War%20of%201854%2C%20Russia%20was%20defeated%20by%20a%20British%20and%20French%20amphibious%20assault%20that%20captured%20Sevastopol.%20In%202024%2C%20the%20fear%20is%20that%20NATO%20ships%20could%20launch%20long-range%20guided%20missiles%20at%20the%20Russian%20heartland.%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%3Cspan%3EThere%20are%20several%20ways%20that%20NATO%20can%20exploit%20this%20fear%2C%20according%20to%20Kaushal%20and%20Balletta.%20Western%20nations%20can%20conduct%20exercises%2C%20forward%20deploy%20nuclear%20submarines%20closer%20to%20Russia%2C%20invest%20in%20drones%20and%20hypersonic%20missiles%2C%20and%20even%20convert%20shipboard%20anti-aircraft%20missiles%20%E2%80%93%20such%20as%20the%20US%20SM-2%20and%20SM-6%20%E2%80%94%20into%20land%20attack%20weapons.%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%3Cspan%3EAs%20Russia%20rebuilds%20its%20military%20to%20replace%20the%20enormous%20losses%20of%20the%20Ukraine%20war%2C%20the%20Kremlin%20may%20feel%20compelled%20to%20divert%20resources%20to%20naval%20rather%20than%20ground%20forces.%20%26quot%3BTo%20the%20extent%20that%20the%20Alliance%20can%20expand%20the%20area%20over%20which%20Russia%20must%20achieve%20sea%20denial%20in%20order%20to%20protect%20itself%20against%20long-range%20strikes%2C%20it%20can%20shape%20the%20contours%20of%20Russian%20force%20regeneration%2C%26quot%3B%20the%20essay%20argued.%20%26quot%3BIt%20can%20achieve%20this%20primarily%20in%20two%20ways%3A%20by%20expanding%20its%20long-range%20land%20attack%20capability%2C%20and%20by%20operating%20on%20new%20vectors%20that%20Russia%20has%20not%20historically%20had%20to%20defend.%26quot%3B%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%3Cspan%3EThe%20Kremlin%20will%20not%20find%20it%20easy%20to%20beef%20up%20its%20maritime%20defenses.%20%26quot%3BWhile%20Russia%20can%20achieve%20sea%20denial%20and%20a%20degree%20of%20sea%20control%20in%20its%20coastal%20seas%2C%20contesting%20freedom%20of%20action%20out%20to%201%2C000%20kilometers%20and%20beyond%20will%20be%20difficult%20and%20costly%20for%20a%20country%20that%20must%20also%20rebuild%20its%20forces%20on%20land%2C%26quot%3B%20said%20the%20essay.%20In%20particular%2C%20while%20Russia%20has%20a%20large%20arsenal%20of%20anti-ship%20missiles%20based%20on%20sea%20and%20land%2C%20it%20lacks%20the%20ISR%20(intelligence%2C%20surveillance%20and%20reconnaissance)%20capabilities%20%3C%2Fspan%3E%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Frussia-putin-invincible-zircon-hypersonic-missile-speed-accuracy-limitations-2023-2%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3E%3Cspan%3Eto%20detect%20distant%20naval%20targets%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fa%3E%3Cspan%3E%20and%20guide%20missiles%20toward%20them.%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%3Cspan%3EShips%20%E2%80%94%20especially%20those%20intended%20for%20blue-water%20rather%20than%20coastal%20operations%20%E2%80%94%20are%20also%20expensive%20to%20build%2C%20maintain%2C%20and%20to%20crews%20at%20a%20time%20when%20the%20Russian%20Army%20and%20Aerospace%20Forces%20are%20in%20desperate%20need%20of%20skilled%20personnel.%20Russian%20shipyards%20are%20already%20overburdened%2C%20and%20new%20vessels%20may%20need%20imported%20components%20that%20are%20blocked%20by%20Western%20sanctions.%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%3Cspan%3EHowever%2C%20the%20West%20also%20suffers%20from%20constraints.%20As%20the%20authors%20acknowledge%2C%20some%20NATO%20members%20on%20Russia's%20border%20%E2%80%94%20such%20as%20Finland%20and%20Norway%20%E2%80%94%20may%20become%20nervous%20about%20making%20Russia%20nervous.%20And%2C%20of%20course%2C%20there%20is%20the%20fact%20that%20Russia%20has%20historically%20feared%20attack%20by%20the%20West%20%E2%80%93%20and%20it%20possesses%20the%20world's%20biggest%20nuclear%20arsenal.%20Stoking%20the%20Kremlin's%20fear%20of%20waves%20of%20cruise%20missiles%20streaking%20in%20from%20the%20sea%20carries%20a%20risk%20of%20nuclear%20escalation.%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%3Cspan%3ENonetheless%2C%20this%20approach%20does%20leverage%20NATO's%20maritime%20advantage.%20Given%20a%20choice%2C%20the%20Kremlin%20would%20probably%20prefer%20to%20spend%20resources%20on%20buying%20tanks%20to%20fight%20in%20Ukraine%20rather%20than%20warships%20to%20guard%20the%20Baltic.%20NATO%20can%20make%20that%20choice%20even%20harder.%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%3Cem%3E%3Cspan%3EMichael%20Peck%20is%20a%20defense%20writer%20whose%20work%20has%20appeared%20in%20Forbes%2C%20Defense%20News%2C%20Foreign%20Policy%20magazine%2C%20and%20other%20publications.%20He%20holds%20a%20MA%20in%20political%20science%20from%20Rutgers%20Univ.%20Follow%20him%20on%20%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fem%3E%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.twitter.com%2F%40mipeck1%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3E%3Cem%3E%3Cspan%3ETwitter%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fem%3E%3C%2Fa%3E%3Cem%3E%3Cspan%3E%20and%20%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fem%3E%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Fin%2Fmipeck%2F%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3E%3Cem%3E%3Cspan%3ELinkedIn%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fem%3E%3C%2Fa%3E%3Cem%3E%3Cspan%3E.%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fem%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cdiv%3ERead%20the%20original%20article%20on%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fnato-navies-can-exploit-russian-fear-keep-it-future-invasions-2024-2%5C%22%3EBusiness%20Insider%3C%2Fa%3E%3C%2Fdiv%3E%22%2C%22published%22%3A